## Selenium Interview Cheat Sheet (Python-ready)

1. What is Selenium?
- Open-source tool to automate web applications
- Controls browsers: Chrome, Firefox, Edge using Python, Java, C#
- Used for UI automation: functional & regression testing
- Integrates with CI/CD pipelines
- Tests web apps faster, accurately, and reliably

2. What is Selenium mainly used for?
- Automates web application testing
- Functional testing: verify features like login/search
- Regression testing: ensure new changes don’t break existing features
- Cross-browser testing & repetitive tasks
- Example: Automated login & form submissions using Python WebDriver

3. Important facts about Selenium
- Open-source & free
- Supports major browsers
- Works with multiple languages: Python, Java, C#
- Components: WebDriver, IDE, Grid
- Cross-platform and CI/CD integration

4. Main components of Selenium
- WebDriver: browser automation, real-user actions
- IDE: browser plugin, records tests for beginners/prototypes
- Grid: parallel execution, cross-browser testing on multiple machines

5. What is Selenium WebDriver?
- Core Selenium component for browser automation
- Simulates real-user actions: open site, click, type, submit, navigate
- Directly communicates with browser
- Fast, supports modern websites
- Most used component in Python projects

6. What is Selenium IDE?
- Browser extension to record actions & auto-generate scripts
- For beginners or quick prototypes
- Uses Selenese; can export to Python, Java, C#, Ruby
- Works only on Chrome & Firefox
- Less flexible than WebDriver

7. What is Selenium Grid?
- Runs tests in parallel on multiple machines, browsers, OS
- Supports cross-browser & cross-platform testing
- Hub/Node architecture
- Speeds up large test suites

8. What is Selenium RC?
- RC = Remote Control, older tool before WebDriver
- Required server as a middleman
- Slower, complex setup, not suitable for modern apps
- Replaced by WebDriver

9. How is WebDriver different from RC?
- WebDriver communicates directly; RC needed server
- Faster, simpler, more reliable
- Supports modern web apps

10. Can Selenium be used for mobile testing?
- Selenium → web automation only
- Use Appium for mobile web applications
- Appium uses WebDriver API for Android & iOS

11. Advantages of Selenium
- Open-source & free
- Multi-browser & multi-language support
- Cross-platform: Windows, Mac, Linux
- Integrates with CI/CD pipelines
- Automates repetitive tasks
- Supports parallel execution
- Improves efficiency, accuracy, test coverage

12. Limitations of Selenium
- Cross-browser issues
- Slower execution for large apps
- Difficulty with dynamic elements
- Limited mobile support (use Appium)
- Cannot automate desktop apps
- No built-in reporting
- High maintenance
- Needs additional tools/frameworks

13. Handling dynamic elements
